About Bella beat

Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products for women. The founder Urška Sršen and Sando Mur,developed beautifully designed technology that informs and inspires women around the world. Collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their own health and habits

Objective

  1. What are some trends in smart device usage?
  2. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  3. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Task

Analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices

Now that all of the table names are under the same format, we will focus on cleaning the date-time format. For sleep_daily the date and time format in the daily_sleep column is in a different format from the rest of the other datasets.The time always equals 12:00:00 AM therefore we will be dropping the unnecessary time. Ensuring a consistent set date-time format throughout the datasets will make merging easier.

activity_daily <- activity_daily %>%
  rename(date = activitydate) %>%
  mutate(date = as_date(date, format = "%m/%d/%Y"))

sleep_daily <- sleep_daily %>%
  rename(date = sleepday) %>%
  mutate(date = as_date(date,format ="%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p" , tz=Sys.timezone()))

Analyzing the data

We want to start by graphing different variables and checking for a correlation or causation.

ggplot(data=daily_merged, aes(x=totalminutesasleep, y=totalsteps)) +
    geom_point(color= "blue") + geom_smooth() + labs(title="Sleep vs. Steps")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

By the displayed table we can see that there is no correlation between the amount of steps a subject takes and the total minutes of sleep. Next I will check the relationship between steps and calories.

ggplot(data=daily_merged, aes(x=totalminutesasleep, y=calories)) +
  geom_point(color= "green") + geom_smooth() + labs(title="Sleep vs. Calories burned")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Just as the previous plot displayed, there is no correlation between sleep and calories burned for the day. Next we will check the relationship between sleep and the time spent in bed.

ggplot(data=daily_merged,aes(x=totalminutesasleep,y=totaltimeinbed))+
  geom_point(color="red") + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Total Time asleep VS Total Time in bed")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

As shown in the graph the relationship between the time spent in bed and time asleep is linear. This is not surprising as most users get around 400-600 minutes of sleep per day (6.67-10 hours). Next we will check the relationship between total time asleep and sedentary minutes.

ggplot(data=daily_merged,aes(x=totalminutesasleep,y=sedentaryminutes))+
  geom_point(color="orange") + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Total Time asleep VS Sedentary Minutes")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

As shown in the graph there is a negative relationship between the total time asleep and sedentary minutes. Meaning the more time spent sedentary, can effect your total time asleep. Based off this data we can tell the marketing company to tell the customers to spend more active minutes rather than being sedentary. Next we will check the relationship between being lightly active and the total amount of sleep.

ggplot(data=daily_merged,aes(x=totalminutesasleep,y=lightlyactiveminutes))+
  geom_point(color="purple") + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Total Time asleep VS Lightly Active Minutes")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

The graph does not seem to show any relationship between both variables.However, comapred to the last graph, you can clearly see that subjects slept around 400 minutes (6.67 hours), and had around 100-250 minutes of light activity. Next we will check the relationship between

ggplot(data=daily_merged,aes(x=totalminutesasleep,y=fairlyactiveminutes))+
  geom_point(color="black") + geom_smooth() + labs(title = "Total Time asleep VS Fairly Active Minutes")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

The graph is simillar to our last graph showing that the subjects were fairly active for 25-50 minutes per day, however the data isn’t accurate due to the fact that the activity of a subject is measured based off of their MET’s. This is the ratio in which your working metabolic rate relative to the resting metabolic rate, this is the way we measure intenseties in workouts. According to the community at fitbit Lightly active is being between 1-1.5 MET’s, Fairly active is 1.5-3, and very active is 3+ MET’s.

Next we will categorize sleep based off the CDC’s recommend sleep, and see if the 30 subjects durring this observation aquired enough sleep throughout the observation.

According to the CDC, the average human sleeps 420 minutes or 7 hours a day.To consider being underslept would mean sleeping less than 7 hours and to be considered overslept they would sleep 541 minutes or 9 hours.

sum(daily_merged$totalminutesasleep <= 419, na.rm=TRUE) 
## [1] 181
sum(daily_merged$totalminutesasleep >= 541, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 39

According to the Fitbit tracker data, it shows that 181 slept more than 419 minutes(7 hours), and 39 slept more than 541 minutes(9 hours).

nrow(sleep_daily) 
## [1] 410

The following code shows us that there are 410 total observations in the sleep_daily data set.We will now add this information to out daily_merged data set.

sleep_type <- daily_merged %>%
  mutate(sleep_type = case_when(totalminutesasleep <= 419 ~ "underslept",
                                totalminutesasleep >= 420 & totalminutesasleep <= 540 ~ "recommended",
                                totalminutesasleep >= 541 ~ "overslept"))
view(sleep_type)

By using the head function we can see the new collumns in our table, and see that we have added our new categories based of the CDC data we talked about earlier.

sleep_type_percent <- sleep_type %>%
  group_by(sleep_type) %>%
  summarise(total = n()) %>%
  mutate(totals = sum(total)) %>%
  group_by(sleep_type) %>%
  summarise(total_percent = total / totals) %>%
  mutate(labels = scales::percent(total_percent))

sleep_type_percent$sleep_type <- factor(sleep_type_percent$sleep_type, levels = c("underslept", "recommended", "overslept"))

head(sleep_type_percent)

Now we create a new table showing the percentages of the subjects number of steps based off of the 2022 study by UT southwestern medical.

steps_type_percent <- steps_type %>%
  group_by(steps_type) %>%
  summarise(total = n()) %>%
  mutate(totals = sum(total)) %>%
  group_by(steps_type) %>%
  summarise(total_percent = total / totals) %>%
  mutate(labels = scales::percent(total_percent))

steps_type_percent$steps_type <- factor(steps_type_percent$steps_type, levels = c("below average", "recommended", "above average"))

Summary and Reccomendations to the company

As we are aware, gathering data related to activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has enabled Bellabeat to provide women with valuable insights into their well-being and behaviors. Since its establishment in 2013, Bellabeat has experienced rapid growth and has swiftly established itself as a technology-driven wellness company focused on women’s health.

After a through analysis of the Fit Bit tracker data I have found different insights that will help the marketing team.

Target market

Full-time working women who spend extended periods at their computers or in meetings, deeply engrossed in their tasks (as indicated by sedentary time data), engage in occasional light physical activity to promote their well-being, as suggested by the analysis of their activity patterns. Nevertheless, there is room for enhancing their daily physical activity to realize health advantages. It’s possible that they could benefit from insights on cultivating healthier habits or finding motivation to sustain their efforts.

what they need to do to improve

The bellabeat app is a guide for women to build better habbits and live a healthy lifestyle.

Recomendations:

  • In-app feature that can help guide women to track sleep habits, and make sure they are getting the recommended hours of sleep.

  • In order to make reccording sleep more efficient they can implemnt a feature that allows you to track your sleep without wearing one of the products, but rather a tap on the screen or a button on the app.

  • An analysis of the users sleep throughout the week, and give tips to help improve the sleep of the users.

  • In-app feature that sets a goal for the amount of steps, and makes sure the user gets the recommended 5,000 steps per day.

  • An analysis of the users steps throughout the week, and give the user some tips to help them achieve the steps goal.

Bellabeat is dedicated to empowering women through its range of health products. Recognizing the vital role sleep plays in maintaining overall well-being,as well as the number of steps we take a day. We believe that the provided suggestions will enhance users’ sleep quality and help users achieve daily steps goals.This will increase app usage and help build a healthier lifestyle for the women at Bellabeat.
